\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:org256bce1}

\subsection{The Internet}
\label{sec:org6e64230}

A network of networks. Allows the World Wide Web a means for existence.

\uline{Nuts and Bolts}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Users}

\begin{itemize}
\item Millions of connected devices.

\item \emph{hosts} as end systems.

\item running \emph{network applications}.
\end{itemize}

\item \textbf{Communication Links}

\begin{itemize}
\item a \emph{medium} of communication.

\item fibre, copper, radio satellite.
\end{itemize}

\item \textbf{Packet Switches}

\begin{itemize}
\item \emph{routers} and \emph{switches,}

\item Help forward the \emph{packets} (chunks of data).
\end{itemize}

\item \textbf{Internet}

\begin{itemize}
\item Interconnected ISPs.
\end{itemize}

\item \textbf{Protocols}

\begin{itemize}
\item Control \emph{sending} and \emph{receiving} of messages.

\item TCP, IP, HTTP, Skype, 802.11
\end{itemize}

\item \textbf{Internet Standards} 

\begin{itemize}
\item \emph{RFC}: Request for Comments

\item \emph{IETF}: Internet Engineering Task Force
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}


\subsection{Protocols}
\label{sec:org961a8cc}

Protocols are sets of instructions for a communication over a specific medium.

Specific messages are sent -------> Specific messages are received

\uline{Define}
\begin{itemize}
\item \emph{Format} of messages
\item \emph{Order} of sending and receiving
\item \emph{Actions taken} on message transmission and receipt
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{ll}
Human & Computer\\
\hline
Hi & TCP connection request\\
Hey & TCP connection response\\
What's the time? & Get \url{http://www.uct.ac.za/index.html}\\
It's 9am & <file>\\
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\begin{enumerate}
\item Protocol Layers
\label{sec:orgcc30f9f}

Since networks are composed of many different complex pieces, we need to organize 
our protocols in layers.

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{llll}
Hosts & Routers & Links & Hardware\\
Applications & Protocols & Hardwards & Software\\
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

Each layer will therefore implement a \emph{service} (through its own internal-layer actions), which in
turn rely on services provided by layer below.

It helps with \uline{Complex Systems}

\begin{itemize}
\item The \emph{explicit structure} of layers allows identification and relationship of complex system's
pieces.

\item \emph{Modularization} eases maintenance and updating of system.
\end{itemize}

\begin{enumerate}
\item Airline Travel
\label{sec:orgfb1ff41}

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{lllll}
ticket (\emph{purchase}) &  &  & ticket (\emph{complain}) & \textbf{ticket}\\
baggage (\emph{check}) &  &  & baggage (\emph{claim}) & \textbf{baggage}\\
gates (\emph{load}) &  &  & gates (\emph{unload}) & \textbf{gate}\\
runway (\emph{takeoff}) &  &  & runway (\emph{land}) & \textbf{takeoff/landing}\\
airplane routing & airplane routing & airplane routing & airplane routing & \textbf{airplane routing}\\
 &  &  &  & \\
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
departure  ------>  air-traffic control centers  ------>  arrival
\end{enumerate}


\item ISO/OSI
\label{sec:org4991286}
Since there are \emph{n users of the computer networks scattered throughout the world,
the /International Organisation of Standardization} (ISO) has developed a standard for how 
systems are to communicate. This standard is called an \emph{Open System Interconnection} (OSI) and can
be referred to as the \textbf{ISO/OSI Reference Model}.

\begin{enumerate}
\item \underline{ISO/OSI Reference Model}
\label{sec:org48aae96}

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{lrll}
Level & Number & Layer Name & Description\\
\hline
\uline{Upper} & 7 & Application & Supporting network applications.\\
" & 6 & Presentation & How data is to be represented in various signals for transmission.\\
" & 5 & Session & Mainly responsible for checkpointing and recovery. Also handles authorization and authentication.\\
\uline{Middle} & 4 & Transport & Provides the logical communication between application processes running on different hosts.\\
" & 3 & Network & Routing of packets/datagrams from source to destination.\\
\uline{Lower} & 2 & Data Link & Handles vice-versa bit-by-bit conversion between data streams and signals to be used by underlying hardware.\\
" & 1 & Physical & Defines how raw-bits are to be transported over a medium.\\
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\item \underline{Internet Protocol Stack and TCP/IP Suite}
\label{sec:org539f3ca}
The \emph{Internet Protocol Stack} is a conceptual model and set of commmunication protocols used to 
satisfy the ISO/OSI reference model for internet communication (as well as many other 
computer networks).


\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{ll}
Layer Name & Associated Protocols\\
\hline
Application & File Transfer Protocol (FTP), Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP), HyperText Transfer Protocol (HTTP)\\
Transport & Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), User Datagram Protocol (UDP)\\
Network & Internet Protocol (IP), \emph{various routing protocols}\\
Data Link & Ethernet, 802.11\\
Physical & "on the wire" bit transfer\\
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\uline{There are 2 layers missing?}
Both the \emph{presentation layer} and the \emph{session layer}, if required, must be implemented by within the
application itself.

\item \underline{ISO/OSI Diagram}
\label{sec:orgedf5dc9}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{Introduction/2020-05-09_11-55-09_screenshot.png}
\end{center}
\href{https://community.fs.com/blog/tcpip-vs-osi-whats-the-difference-between-the-two-models.html}{image reference}
\end{enumerate}
\end{enumerate}




\subsection{Network Structure}
\label{sec:orgd547286}

\subsubsection{Scale and Scope}
\label{sec:org6f7361c}

\begin{enumerate}
\item LAN (Local Area Network)
\label{sec:org7fa4fac}
A network of interconnected hosts that covers a small geographical region (e.g. a house, a school,
etc..).

\item MAN (Metropolitan Area Network)
\label{sec:orgf5bdf25}
A network of interconnected hosts that covers a geographical region the size of a metropolitan
area (e.g. Google's new wifi towers in the Cape Flats).

\item WAN (Wide Area Network)
\label{sec:org99b12c8}
A network of interconnected hosts that cover an extremely large geographical region (e.g. the 
internet is a WAN).
\end{enumerate}



\subsubsection{Transmission Mode}
\label{sec:orga72b2ed}

\begin{enumerate}
\item Unicast
\label{sec:orgc14b053}
Message sent by \emph{one} sender to \emph{one} receiver.

\textbf{S -> R}

\item Multicast
\label{sec:orgb1b2aed}
Message sent by one sender to a set/list of recipients.

\textbf{S} -> \textbf{[R\(_{\text{1,R}}\)\(_{\text{2,R}}\)\(_{\text{3}}\)]}

\item Anycast
\label{sec:org4ff3837}
Message sent by one sender to any one member of a set (usually the node closest to the sender). 

\textbf{S} -> \textbf{R\(_{\text{1}}\)} | \textbf{R\(_{\text{2}}\)} | \textbf{R\(_{\text{3}}\)}

\item Broadcast
\label{sec:org775f657}
Message sent by one sender to everyone.

\textbf{S} -> \textbf{R\(_{\text{(1..n)}}\)}
\end{enumerate}


\subsubsection{Regions}
\label{sec:org5673f33}
\begin{enumerate}
\item Network Edge
\label{sec:org70fb00d}
\emph{Hosts} dwell here. Generally categorized as \emph{clients} and \emph{servers}.

\item Access Networks / Physical Media
\label{sec:org9511b48}
Wired and wireless communication links, commonly managed by \emph{Internet Service Providers} (ISPs).

\item Network Core
\label{sec:orgf27baba}
Interconnected routers producing a network of networks (the internet).

\begin{enumerate}
\item Packet Switching
\label{sec:orgc4d6662}
A message is broken up into many different packets which are sent independently down their 
individual optimum network paths, being forwarded from router to router until they reach their
destination.

\begin{enumerate}
\item Packets
\label{sec:org065bf99}

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Header} - contains addresses and other data required for the packet to reach its destination.

\item \textbf{Payload} - actual data being sent.
\end{itemize}
\end{enumerate}

\item Routing
\label{sec:org59ef082}
Determines the route from source to destination taken by the packet.

\item Forwarding
\label{sec:org7ce1e6c}
Directs packet from router's input to appropriate router output.
\end{enumerate}
\end{enumerate}


\subsubsection{Network of Networks}
\label{sec:orga172ea0}
Important to note that the evolution of the \emph{network of network} that composes the internet is driven
by \textbf{economic} and \textbf{national policies} (obviously, that's why ISPs suck).

Do to the sheer number of potential users of the internet, it is downright impossible to connect
every individual network together. For this reason, \textbf{access ISPs} (Internet Service Providers) have
been established as administrators and connection hubs for large clusters of networks.

When pondering how in turn these (millions of) ISPs should communicate with eachother, we come
across a few options.

\begin{enumerate}
\item \uline{Connect each access ISP to every other access ISP?}
\end{enumerate}

This scales horribly - O(N\(^{\text{2}}\)) connections!

\begin{enumerate}
\item \uline{Connect each access ISP to a global transit ISP (a central hub)?}
\end{enumerate}

This seems viable but who will control this? If it looks good competitors will join the game.

\begin{enumerate}
\item \uline{Hierarchal ISP Structure} (winner)
\end{enumerate}

\begin{enumerate}
\item Current Topology
\label{sec:org6f4ae0f}


\uline{Pre-Defs}

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Peering} - neither party pays for the other in exchange of traffic, they rather souly gain
revenue from their own customers.

\item \textbf{IP Transit} - money is exchanged between parties that agree to peer with one another.
\end{itemize}

\uline{Baseline}

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{rlll}
Tier & Description & Peering Policy & Examples\\
\hline
1 & Exchange traffic with other \emph{Tier 1 providers} & \emph{Strict} peering agreements (mostly Tier 2 ISPs and Content Provider Networks) & Hibernia Networks, Cogent Communications\\
2 & Exchanges traffic between the \emph{Tier 1 and Tier 3 providers} & \emph{Settlement-Free} peering (neither party pays but rather attains revenue from its own customers) & Vodafone, British Telekom, GTT Communications\\
3 & Purchases internet transit from Tier 2 providers and delivers internet access to end systems (homes, schools, etc.) & \emph{IP Transit} with Tier 2 providers & Mweb, Afrihost, Telkom, Neotel, <your-provider-here>\\
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\uline{ISP Connections}

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Internet Exchange Point (IXP)} - a point where multiple ISPs interconnect so
\end{itemize}
the internet can exist.


\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Peering Link} - traffic exchange points for multiple ISPs (for \emph{peering}).
\end{itemize}

\uline{Extras}

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Content Provider Networks} (like Google, Microsoft, etc..) - may have their own external networks
\end{itemize}
to allow faster service delivery. These networks can harbour connections to any ISP as well as
IXPs

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Regional ISPs/Nets} (classified as a \emph{WAN}) - Act as hubs for geographically clustered access ISPs
\end{itemize}
in order to interface with global ISPs (and Content Provider Networks). Examples including \emph{openserve},
\emph{frogfoot}, and \emph{neotel}.


